    faq: [
 { question: "Can I use vitamin C serum if I have sensitive skin?", answer: "Yes! Start with gentler derivatives like Sodium Ascorbyl Phosphate or Magnesium Ascorbyl Phosphate instead of pure L-ascorbic acid. Begin with lower concentrations (5-10%) and patch test behind your ear for 48 hours before full-face application. Gradually increase frequency from twice weekly to daily as tolerance builds." },
 { question: "How long does vitamin C serum take to show results?", answer: "Initial radiance improvements appear within 1-2 weeks. Visible fading of dark spots and post-acne marks typically occurs in 4-8 weeks. Significant collagen building and wrinkle reduction requires 12+ weeks of consistent daily use. Patience and consistency are essential”don't give up too soon!" },
 { question: "Can I apply vitamin C around my eyes?", answer: "Yes, but use extreme caution. The eye area is delicate. Either use a dedicated vitamin C eye cream formulated for this sensitive area, or dilute your facial serum with moisturizer before applying around the orbital bone. Never apply directly on eyelids unless the product specifically states it's safe for that use." },
 { question: "Does vitamin C make skin more sun-sensitive?", answer: "Initially, yes”vitamin C can increase photosensitivity during the first few weeks of use. This is precisely why daily sunscreen application is NON-NEGOTIABLE. However, long-term vitamin C use actually provides photoprotection by neutralizing free radicals from UV exposure. Always pair with SPF 50+." },
 { question: "Should I use vitamin C in the morning or at night?", answer: "Morning application is ideal because vitamin C's antioxidant properties provide daytime protection against UV damage and pollution. However, if you experience any sensitivity, nighttime use is acceptable. Some people use it twice daily for accelerated results”start with once daily and build tolerance." },
 { question: "What does oxidized vitamin C look like?", answer: "Fresh vitamin C serum is clear to very pale yellow. Oxidation causes it to turn orange, amber, or brown. Once it reaches dark orange or brown, it's lost potency and should be discarded. To extend shelf life: store in refrigerator, keep bottle tightly closed, choose airless pump packaging, and use within 3 months of opening." },
 { question: "Can teenagers use vitamin C serum?", answer: "Absolutely! Vitamin C is excellent for teenage skin concerns like acne scars, hyperpigmentation, and oil control. Choose gentler derivatives (SAP or MAP) and lower concentrations (5-10%). It's a fantastic preventive anti-aging ingredient to start early, paired with daily sunscreen." },
 { question: "Is expensive vitamin C serum worth the cost?", answer: "Not necessarily. While luxury serums often have superior formulation and stability technology, many budget options (Timeless, Maelove, CeraVe) deliver comparable results. Focus on: concentration (10-20%), pH level (below 3.5), packaging (dark bottle or airless pump), and fresh formula”not price tag." }
 ],
